{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636593"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17591"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10305"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56956"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9994"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of nutrients in the small intestine triggers several feedback mechanisms that affect gastric function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the enterogastric reflex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhances gastric mucosal blood flow","Inhibits gastric secretion and motility","Increases gastric emptying rate","Promotes gastric muscle contraction","Stimulates gastric acid production"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the enterogastric reflex is the \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of gastric secretion and motility\u003C/strong\u003E. This reflex is triggered when nutrients (particularly fats and proteins) enter the duodenum, leading to the release of hormones like cholecystokinin and secretin that slow gastric function. This reflex can be stimulated by duodenal distension or a lowering of the pH. The reflex acts on the astral G cells to reduce the release of gastrin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of gastric acid production\u003C/strong\u003E - The enterogastric reflex actually reduces acid secretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased gastric emptying rate\u003C/strong\u003E - The reflex slows gastric emptying to prevent overwhelming the small intestine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotion of gastric muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E - The reflex reduces gastric motility and contractility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced gastric mucosal blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - The reflex does not significantly affect mucosal blood flow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis negative feedback mechanism helps regulate the delivery of chyme to the small intestine, preventing nutrient overload and optimising absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The enterogastric reflex inhibits gastric secretion and motility when nutrients enter the small intestine.","Cholecystokinin and secretin are key hormones that mediate the enterogastric reflex.","The enterogastric reflex helps regulate the rate of gastric emptying to optimise nutrient absorption."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56956"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56956"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T16:54:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T16:54:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10305"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:2